<Fragment slot="intro">
<p>An LG dryer drum roller replacement costs $280–350 including parts and labor — the full set of four OEM rollers runs $40–60, labor $200–240. Our LG Dryer Repair techs spin and inspect the drum to confirm the rollers are the real source of the noise before quoting, so you don't pay to replace good parts — call (323) 990-7550.</p>
<p>LG dryer drum roller replacement costs <strong>$280–350 total</strong> in Los Angeles, Orange County, and Ventura County — full set of 4 OEM rollers, labor, and 1-year warranty included. The $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair. About half our drum roller calls turn out to be simpler fixes that cost less. This page explains exactly what drives the price and what to check before calling.</p>
</Fragment>

<h2>What's Included in the $280–350 Price</h2>
<p>On most LG models the four-roller OEM set is only $40–60, so the $280–350 you pay is mostly the labor our LG Dryer Repair techs put into pulling the drum completely out to reach them — adding the idler pulley while we're inside is just $15–25 more in parts, not another labor charge.</p>
<p>We replace all four drum rollers as a complete set — not just the one that's making noise. LG dryers have four rollers supporting the drum, and they wear at similar rates. If one is squeaking, the others have the same mileage on them. Replacing only the noisy roller means the others start failing within months — a second service call that costs almost as much as the first. Replacing all four at once costs marginally more in parts but saves you that second labor charge. We explain this on-site before we start.</p>
<p>The price also includes checking the idler pulley, motor bearings, and drive belt while we have the drum out. These components are fully exposed during roller replacement. On machines 8+ years old in Calabasas and Glendale, we frequently find the idler pulley is also starting to seize. Adding the pulley at the same visit costs $15–25 extra in parts with no additional labor. Much cheaper than a return call.</p>

<h2>How Much Does It Cost to Replace Drum Rollers on an LG Dryer?</h2>
<p><strong>$280–350 total</strong> for most LG models. Breakdown:</p>
<p><strong>OEM drum roller set (4 rollers):</strong> $40–60. LG DLEX and DLGX front-loading models use tri-roller assemblies; older DLE series use simpler dual-roller configurations. Common part numbers: AGM75510755 (most DLGX/DLEX) and 4581EL2002H (older DLE/DLG). The DLEX3900 series and similar premium models use assemblies that run $55–75 for the set. We confirm the correct set before arrival.</p>
<p><strong>Labor:</strong> $200–240. This covers front panel removal, belt removal, complete drum removal, roller replacement, belt re-routing with correct tension, reassembly, and a full test cycle. Roller replacement takes 60–90 minutes on most LG models. Tight laundry closet installations in Santa Monica condos or stacked configurations in Pasadena add 15–20 minutes.</p>
<p><strong>Rollers plus idler pulley together:</strong> $300–380 total — the incremental cost of adding the pulley is minimal since we're already inside the machine.</p>

<h2>Is It Worth Replacing LG Dryer Rollers?</h2>
<p>Almost always yes. At $280–350, drum roller replacement costs less than 25% of a new comparable LG dryer ($800–1,500). For premium DLGX models that originally cost $1,200–1,800, the repair represents just 15–20% of replacement cost while keeping the unit's advanced features and sensor drying. A quality roller replacement extends dryer life by 5–8 years on a machine that's otherwise in good shape.</p>
<p>The calculation gets harder on machines 12+ years old where we find multiple components failing alongside the rollers. If the <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element</a> is also marginal and the <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">thermal fuse</a> has already blown once, the combined repair starts approaching new dryer territory. We'll walk you through the math on-site before we start — we're not pushing a combined repair that doesn't make financial sense.</p>
<p>For dryers under 8 years old with rollers as the primary issue — from Burbank to Moorpark to Irvine — repair is almost always the obvious choice.</p>

<h2>How Do I Know If My LG Dryer Rollers Are Bad?</h2>
<p><strong>Squeaking or squealing</strong> that starts when the dryer runs and gets louder as it warms up. The sound is rhythmic — tied to drum rotation speed. You can sometimes quiet it briefly by pressing lightly on the drum through the door opening while it runs.</p>
<p><strong>Thumping</strong> that's consistent and may settle after a few minutes. Usually means a roller has developed a flat spot from sitting idle. The flat spot causes one thump per rotation until the roller warms up. On older machines the thump never fully goes away as the flat spot deepens.</p>
<p><strong>Drum rotation feels uneven.</strong> Open the door and spin the drum slowly by hand. Smooth with steady resistance is normal. Grinding, catching, or resistance that's heavier at specific points means roller wear.</p>
<p><strong>Clothes bunching on one side</strong> instead of tumbling evenly — worn rollers can cause the drum to wobble slightly, disrupting the tumbling pattern.</p>
<p>About 50% of drum roller calls we get across LA County, Orange County, and Ventura County turn out to be simpler than expected — loose connections, alignment issues, or a foreign object lodged against the drum — that resolve without parts replacement. We always diagnose before recommending parts.</p>

