<h2>Questions About LG Dryer Drum Roller Replacement Cost</h2>

<h3>How much does it cost to replace drum rollers on an LG dryer?</h3>
<p>$280–350 total in Los Angeles, Orange County, and Ventura County — full set of 4 OEM rollers, labor, and 1-year warranty. The $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair. Same-day service available.</p>

<h3>Should I repair or replace my LG dryer if the drum rollers are bad?</h3>
<p>For dryers under 8 years old with rollers as the primary issue, repair is almost always the right call. At $280–350, you're paying less than 25% of new dryer cost while getting 5–8 more years of service. We'll tell you honestly on-site if we find other issues that change that math.</p>

<h3>Do you replace all four drum rollers or just the bad ones?</h3>
<p>We replace the full set of four. All four have the same mileage — replacing only the noisy one means the others fail within months and you're paying for a second service call. The incremental cost of all four vs two is minimal in parts.</p>

<h3>How do I know if my LG dryer rollers are bad?</h3>
<p>Squeaking or squealing tied to drum rotation speed, especially getting louder as the dryer warms up. Rhythmic thumping that settles after a few minutes of running. Drum feels uneven or grinds when you spin it slowly by hand. Clothes bunching on one side instead of tumbling evenly.</p>

<h3>How long does LG dryer drum roller replacement take?</h3>
<p>60–90 minutes on-site for most LG models. The drum comes out completely. We check idler pulley, motor bearings, and belt condition while inside and run a full test cycle before leaving.</p>

<h3>Can you come today?</h3>
<p>Yes — call (323) 990-7550. Same-day service across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County, typically 2–4 hours from your call.</p>

<h3>Does LG dryer drum roller replacement come with a warranty?</h3>
<p>Yes — every LG Dryer Repair drum roller job includes a 1-year warranty on both parts and labor. We replace the full set of four OEM rollers, and the $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Will replacing the drum rollers stop the grinding and thumping noise?</h3>
<p>Yes, when worn rollers are the actual source — which we confirm by spinning the drum by hand before quoting. Grinding, squealing tied to drum speed, and rhythmic thumping are classic roller wear. We also check the idler pulley and belt while the drum is out, since a worn pulley can make a similar noise.</p>

